					<div style="text-align: justify">
					Negros Occidental is a province located in the Western Visayas region of the Philippines. It occupies the northwestern half of the island of Negros, with Negros Oriental to the southeast. Known as the "Sugar Bowl of the Philippines," it is one of the country's top producers of sugar. The provincial capital is Bacolod City, which is also the largest city in the province and known for the MassKara Festival. Other significant cities include San Carlos, Escalante, Sagay, Victorias, Silay, Bago, La Carlota, Kabankalan and Sipalay.
					Negros Occidental is rich in cultural heritage, with many preserved ancestral houses and historical landmarks, particularly in cities like Silay and Talisay. The Panaad sa Negros Festival dubbed as the "Mother of all Festivals" is one of the biggest festivals where the 13 cities and 19 municipalities converge in one location for the to celebrate the promise of the province to its people. The province also boasts beautiful beaches, mountains, caves, waterfalls and dive spots. Notable attractions include the Mt. Kanlaon Natural Park, Lakawon Island, Sipaway Island and the Sipalay City's beaches and diving spots.
					Negros Occidental's blend of natural beauty, cultural richness, and economic vitality makes it a significant province in the Philippines.</div>
